<TEXT>
The United States and Madagascar 
signed a 22 million agreement for a fiveyear national infant 
health vaccination program the government announced Thursday 
The program financed with a grant from the United States Agency 
for International Development is aimed at reducing infant 
mortality in Madagascar an island nation in the Indian Ocean off 
the eastern coast of Africa Madagascars infant mortality rate was 
109 per 1000 births in 1985 according to the World Bank 
The island nation has a population of 106 million growing at 
28 percent a year 
The project will be administered by the United Nations Children 
Fund to vaccinate 7 million children ages 14 and 21 million 
children over 5 They will be vaccinated against tetanus 
diptheria measles and whooping cough 
The program will also provide preventive malaria medicine and 
vaccination against tetanus for 2 million pregnant women 
</TEXT>
